{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:58:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:58:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1237"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.75,0.1,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104407"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86737"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"439"},{"type":"tags","id":"8850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12279"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104407"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a two-week history of a painless swelling of his right upper eyelid (Image). He reports no changes to vision and no eyelid discharge. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pupillary reflexes are intact bilaterally. Visual acuity is 6/5 in his left eye and 6/6 in his right eye (uncorrected). Extraocular movements are normal and non-painful. Visual field testing finds no deficits. Palpation of the nodule finds no associated tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sebaceous cyst","Chalazion","Hordeolum","Basal cell carcinoma","Herpes zoster ophthalmicus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Echalazion\u003C/strong\u003E. A chalazion is a consequence of Meibomian gland obstruction. Chalazions tend to affect the upper eyelid more so than the lower eyelid and may vary in size. There is a non-infective granulomatous inflammatory reaction to contents of the Meibomian gland (sebum) leaking into surrounding tissue, and the obstruction presents as a painless nodule within the tarsal plate or lid margin. A hot compress and eyelid margin hygiene twice daily generally resolves most cases, but persisting chalazion may require incision and drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esebaceous cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is also a possibility given the appearance, however these are less common on the eyelid compared to a chalazion. Sebaceous cysts also tend to be more mobile than a chalazion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHordeolums (styes)\u003C/strong\u003E are acute infective obstruction of sebaceous glands of the eye (Meibomian or Zeis). Hordeolums generally develop more acutely than chalazion and patients will often report pain and pre-septal cellulitis, which is absent in this case. Oral antibiotics and careful lid hygiene is recommened.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal cell carcinomas\u003C/strong\u003E can occur on the eyelids, they typically appear as a non-healing ulcer or nodule that may bleed. The history of recent onset and examination findings are more consistent with a benign lesion in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster ophthalmicus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a painful vesicular rash in the distribution of the trigeminal nerve, often accompanied by systemic symptoms such as fever. The lesions may be multiple over the forehead and upper eyelid unilaterally. The absence of pain and vesicles makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chalazion result from a non-infective obstruction of Meibomian glands, and more commonly occurs on the upper eyelids."],"references":["Carlisle RT, Digiovanni  J. Differential Diagnosis of the Swollen Red Eyelid.  Am Fam Physician. 2015; 92:106-12","Sun, M. Huang, S. Huilgol, S. Selva, D. \u0022Eyelid lesion in general practice\u0022 Australian Journal of General Practice August 2019: 48 (8) Accessed 17 June 2024. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-03-19-4875"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86737"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1237"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17442"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17442"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b915aca6-5cd1-492d-9a2c-bf4b56105472.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b915aca6-5cd1-492d-9a2c-bf4b56105472.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86737"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T00:05:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T00:05:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1237"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104407"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,